<activity><title>Intercepts and Vertex</title>

<task><p>How do we find the <m>y</m>-intercept of a parabola from its equation?</p></task>

<task><p>How do we find the <m>x</m>-intercepts of a parabola from its equation?</p></task>

<task><p>Recall that to find the average of two numbers we add them up, and divide the result by 2.</p>
  <p><ol>
    <li><p>If the <m>x</m>-intercepts of a parabola are <m>x=p</m> and <m>x=q</m>, what is the <m>x</m>-coordinate of its vertex?</p></li>
    <li><p>If the <m>x</m>-intercepts of a parabola are <m>x=0</m> and <m>x=\dfrac{-b}{a}</m>, what is the <m>x</m>-coordinate of its vertex?</p></li></ol></p></task>

<task><p>How do we find the <m>y</m>-coordinate of the vertex from the equation?</p></task>

              <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
              <p>This Activity leads students to the formula for the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the vertex. After deriving the formula, demonstrate that it works on the graphs in the prevous Activity.</p></commentary>

<task><p>Describe how each of the three parameters <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> affect the graph of the basic parabola.</p>
    <p><ol>
      <li><p><m>y=ax^2</m></p></li>
      <li><p><m>y=x^2 + c</m></p></li>
      <li><p><m>y=x^2 + bx</m></p></li></ol></p></task>
</activity>

<subsection><title>Check Your Understanding</title>
<p><ol>
<li><p>What are the <m>x</m>-intercepts of the graph of <m>y=x^2-16</m>?  What are the <m>x</m>-intercepts of the graph of <m>y=x^2-16x</m>?
</p></li>
<li><p>What is the axis of symmetry of the graph of <m>y=x^2-16</m>?  What is the axis of symmetry of the graph of <m>y=x^2-16</m>?</p></li>
<li><p>How is the graph of <m>y=2x^2+5</m> different from the basic parabola?  What are the coordinates of its vertex?</p></li>
<li><p>Compare the graphs of <m>y=x^2-25</m> and <m>y=25-x^2</m>.</p></li></ol></p>
</subsection>

<subsection><title>Wrap Up</title>
<p>In this Lesson, we worked on the following skills and goals related to quadratic models:</p>
<p><ul>
 <li><p>Describe the effect of each of the parameters <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> on the graph of a parabola</p></li>
<li><p>Find the <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-intercepts of a parabola</p></li> 
<li><p>Find the vertex of a parabola</p></li>
<li><p>Sketch the graph of a parabola</p></li></ul></p>

<commentary audience="instructor"><title>Questions for Writing or Discussion</title>
<p><ol>
<li><p>Describe what the parameter <m>a</m> tells you about the graph of <m>y=ax^2</m>.</p></li>
<li><p>Explain why the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the vertex is the average of the <m>x</m>-intercepts of the graph.</p></li>
<li><p>Describe the differences between the graphs of <m>y=x^2-4</m> and <m>y=x^2-4x</m>.</p></li>
<li><p>Explain why the graph of <m>y=x^2-2</m> is shifted down 2 units compared to the basic parabola.</p></li>
</ol></p></commentary>
</subsection>

